How Travel Prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies then sold in most cases only to the socialist block, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore took vacations on the beaches of the RDA (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) in Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslavia regime moved to the west and the travel of Czech tourists was then quite limited.
A great barrier to socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist block (i.e. also the Czechoslovakian people) were not allowed to travel freely and individually, not even by socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West in those days, but one had to put on the hill with a bag of sleep and spend the same night, or have "good-known" in the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The so-called "change promise" that was the condition for Western travel was not granted to the "politically less reliable agent", who could not travel in absolute terms.
The Czechoslovakian currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without the guarantee of change, it was not possible to obtain resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
Most of the Czechs had their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of caravans and summer houses, which the Czechs would buy. This custom still persisted.
The way the Czechs travel has suffered a genuine revolution since 1989.
While it was not until 1989 that the holidays in the RDA or Bulgaria were no more, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, from which today we are no longer aware, the fact that the current favorite destination, Croatia, was unable to travel freely until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia from then on.
At the beginning of the 1990s, visa exemption was imposed to travel to the neighbouring states of Western Europe, resulting in a huge amount of short-term visits, particularly in Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see a map of the journeys to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, checkout groups in the parks in the countryside shops were slept, as our income did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the checks of that time was to bring with you the food (conservatives, embutes, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists were finally able, after decades, to buy free Western currency.
Our standard of living also increased the average wages with him, which caused an increase in travel demand about 1997.
With the increase in travel demand, agencies began, from 1997 on a regular basis, to prepare trips using charter flights, which made the prices of travel in comparison with the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts by passenger volume.
At the end of the 90th century, the Czechs had already traveled almost all the developed countries, except the United States, which made our journeys even more simple.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism took place in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Chequia to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists have taken place. This winter will already fly directly from Chequia to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries are currently visiting about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-conflict development, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the U.S. removed visas for Czech tourists, with what our country had become among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent abroad on trips to over 15,000 Czech crowns per head, including expenses at the station.
