The North Stream, new Russian gas entrance door in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea, has already been in service.
Gas must be provided to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pump.
Last March, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated in the streets of the Baltic, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, in the opening of the North Stream, the new gas pipeline that directly communicates, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Accordingly, the German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart of the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have driven along the wheel that controls Russian gas entry into the western European network.
With this new pipeline, each year it will reach 27.5 million cubic metres of additional Russian gas to Western Europe through a 1,224 km first tube that communicates the region of St. Petersburg with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be concluded at the end of 2012 to provide a total of 55,000 million cubic metres of gas, i.e. sufficient to cover the entire French consumption.
In addition, it is already about the possibility of building a third pipe by the same route.
For Gazprom, the end of this huge work presents a win area.
Poland and the Baltic countries had firmly opposed the project.
In fact, the North Stream will allow direct gas supply to Germany, avoiding land transit by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Unfortunately, these two countries lose some of their power: it will be more difficult for them to influence Russia by putting it in danger of closing access to the markets in Western Europe.
In the light of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream as a "new fraternal-Soviet-Soviet pact" with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically delicate.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe's energy, as the project has generated a gap between the Western and Western Europeans.
Russia has been able, in just five years, to triune its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our association with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," François Fillon confirmed during the opening of the gas pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the large gas sector contracts are as political as economic as possible.
All of this explains the broad sounds in the faces of the Gasprom directives, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline also implies technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-recovered steel to protect it from the waves of ships.
It is supported in the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mines from World War II.
"It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, by caution," says Jens Müller, a spokesman for North Stream society.
It was also necessary to eliminate the protection measures for the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal mirror that weighs as 242 Eiffel Towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: either by valves or by maintenance stations.
A control platform was foreseen in the waters of Sweden, but the project's managers gave up on the fact that the Swedish people were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to be established permanently in the sea at its shores.
"In case of averaging, we'll interrupt the gas step in less than a minute," needs Jens Müller.
In the case of escape, the gas of the pipeline will therefore be released to the atmosphere.
However, constructioners consider it unlikely that a flight will occur, as they have planned alliances that, according to the forecasts, will have one flight every 100,000 years.
The control of the status of the gas pipeline shall be ensured by a submarine robot drawn by a vessel carrying out external inspections, as well as by a device that circles through the gas pipeline inside.
With the shape of a pure, it enters inside the tube, which has a diameter of a meter, and moves with gas.
At its arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformities.
The gas pipeline has been designed to operate for five years without any need for repair.
Gas circulation is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have united their forces to carry out this project.
The lead company is Gazprom, which holds 51 per cent of the participants.
To her, the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez group (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint company called Nord Stream, responsible for building and exploiting the gas pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Later, Gazprom rented to that company, for a period of twenty-five years renewables, the total capacity of gas transport.
"Gazprom will pay for its total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," needs Jens Müller.
The funding for the construction of gas pipelines has been completed by 30 per cent with the contribution of shareholders and 70 per cent with bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be EUR 7,400 million for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom takes the risk of spending alone.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on an arena coast planted with pines.
A few valves, with 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas to arrive before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last March, the terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
Total capacity will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
