Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The XV Week for the employment of disabled people begins today.
Despite a public policy resolution, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled persons doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Dissatisfied?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
"The progress achieved over the past 15 years is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there's still too much to do."
It should be noted that disabled persons continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37% is over 50 years old (17% average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% has not finished the study, and only 10,000 of the 2.3 million students in higher education are disabled.
Finally, the long-term pairs are very extensive among them: 53 per cent for disabled persons, compared to 38 per cent of the average.
In other words, there are many issues that are particularly difficult to return to the working world and that "constitutionally constitute the problem," says Christian Grapin, Director-General of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mentality progresses, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS- Entrepreneurship for the City indicated that the managers concerned had "a level of knowledge on low disability", with "extreme representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hireing 6% of disabled workers, a target set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures from 2008, a ratio of 2.6 per cent is reached.
"We are now reaching around 3%," said Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the agency responsible for revoking the contributions of companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of establishment "submitted to this contribution", as well as the amounts paid, has decreased between 2007 and 2011, ranging from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, has generated a great pressure on companies," Pierre Blanc explains.
"But this improvement also reflects true consciousness, especially among the large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of the companies that have between 20 and 49 workers have employees who are disabled in their home, compared to 82 per cent of the companies between 100 and 199 workers.
